      <hedline>
        <hl1>Cuba's Young Pioneers</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Barry Farber letter responds to June 14 Lessons column, which described Cuba's Young Pioneers as 'a youth group that many Miamians have attacked as one of Castro's political arms,' as if they might be mistaken in that belief</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pride and Politics in School for Young People in Cuba,'' by Randal C. Archibold (Lessons column, June 14):</p>
        <p>The mission of the Pioneers is one aspect of Communism I've never before seen challenged. From Lenin on, these groups in every Communist country have been formed to indoctrinate the young in Communist ideology.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pride and Politics in School for Young People in Cuba,'' by Randal C. Archibold (Lessons column, June 14):</p>
        <p>The mission of the Pioneers is one aspect of Communism I've never before seen challenged. From Lenin on, these groups in every Communist country have been formed to indoctrinate the young in Communist ideology.</p>
        <p>It was fascinating, therefore, to see Mr. Archibold describe the Pioneros de Jose Marti as ''a youth group that many Miamians have attacked as one of Castro's political arms.''  Would he have described the Hitler Youth in Nazi Germany as ''a youth group that many Jewish refugees in New York attack as one of Hitler's political arms''?</p>
        <p>BARRY FARBER  New York, June 14, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is a talk-radio host.</p>
      </block>
